<h2>
    <a href="/blog/power-spectra-for-blue-and-uniform-noise/">Power Spectra for &quot;Blue&quot; and Uniform Noise</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    
    on 24 Apr 2017
</h6>





<a href="/blog/power-spectra-for-blue-and-uniform-noise/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/poisson_disc/.thumbnails/periodograms.png/periodograms-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>The <a href="/blog/poisson-disc-sampling-in-python/">previous post</a> provided some code for generating Poisson disc noise (in which no point the sample is closer than some fixed distance from any other). Here is a short program to calculate the power spectrum of this noise and compare it with the spectrum for the same number of points drawn from a uniform distribution.</p>




